 Back in Philly, the second half of the show welcomes hometown favorite Amos Lee.
 His fifth LP, Mountains of Sorrow, Rivers of Song, is out on Blue Note Records this month,
 and its possibly Lee's most stylistically adventurous release to date. While staying true to 
the singer-songwriter template that earned him an international following, Lee ventures into old timey 
country and ragtime sounds in some moments of the album, while rolling out some expansive rockers at others.
